17","1147":"1147","20 February 1147":"20. februar 1147","1065":"1065","1162":"1162","1084":"1084","1172":"1172","van 1120 to 1147":"fra 1120 til 1147","1070":"1070","1108":"1108","Herzogtum Kleve, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Kleve"},"nl":{"1084–20 February 1147":"1084–20 februari 1147","1084–1147":"1084–1147","1108–1162":"1108–1162","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1070–1117":"1070–1117","1065–Female":"1065–Overleden","1129":"1129","1117":"1117","1147":"1147","20 February 1147":"20 februari 1147","1065":"1065","1162":"1162","1084":"1084","1172":"1172","van 1120 to 1147":"van 1120 to 1147","1070":"1070","1108":"1108","Herzogtum Kleve, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Kleve"},"en":{"1084–20 February 1147":"1084–20 February 1147","1084–1147":"1084–1147","1108–1162":"1108–1162","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1070–1117":"1070–1117","1065–Female":"1065–Deceased","1129":"1129","1117":"1117","1147":"1147","20 February 1147":"20 February 1147","1065":"1065","1162":"1162","1084":"1084","1172":"1172","van 1120 to 1147":"from 1120 to 1147","1070":"1070","1108":"1108","Herzogtum Kleve, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Cleves","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Kleve","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from Kleve (earlier Cleve) in Lower Rhineland, Westphalia, or Schleswig-Holstein. The placename probably derives from an old topographic term <i>cleve</i> ‘swamp’. Compare   Cleve  .","German: variant of   Klever   2.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Kleiva, from Old Norse <i>kleif</i>, <i>klif</i> ‘cliff, rocky ascent with a road or path’."],"variants":[{"name":"Klever","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Ulrike.","German and Dutch: habitational name for someone from Kleve in the Rhineland or Schleswig-Holstein (see   Kleve   1).","German: from Middle Low German <i>klēver</i> ‘clover, meadow’, also ‘resin, turpentine’, hence a metonymic occupational name either for a farmer who grew clover or for someone who collected resin and distilled turpentine. In the Alemannic area this was also a nickname for a bungler. Compare   Cleaver   and   Clever  ."]},{"name":"Kleven","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Berger, Hjalmer, Jalmer, Knute, Maren, Obert, Thor, Thorval.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads all over Norway named Kleven, from the definite singular form of   Kleve  . Compare   Cleven   and   Cleveland  .","Dutch and German: rare variant of   Cleven  ."]},{"name":"Cleve","meanings":["English: variant of   Cliff  .","German: variant of   Kleve  ."]}]},{"name":"Arnold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  Jewish: Yiddish contracted form of   Aaron .","2  English: short form of   Arnold ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Arnold I. von Kleve was born in 1084, in Cleves, his father, Dietrich III. von Kleve, was 15 and his mother, Berta de Montjoie, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Ida van Leuven-Brabant. In 1117, at the age of 33, his occupation is listed as vogt des stifts zyfflich. He died on 20 February 1147, in his hometown, at the age of 63, and was buried in Cleves."},"et":{"1084–20 February 1147":"1084–20. veebruar 1147","1084–1147":"1084–1147","1108–1162":"1108–1162","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1070–1117":"1070–1117","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1129":"1129","1117"